150
00:14:17,558 --> 00:14:18,719
Indictments.

151
00:14:18,798 --> 00:14:20,758
Viktor Bryukhanov,

152
00:14:20,838 --> 00:14:22,959
Anatoly Dyatlov,

153
00:14:23,038 --> 00:14:24,998
Nikolai Fomin,

154
00:14:25,078 --> 00:14:27,958
are accused of violating
Article 220 Section 2

155
00:14:28,039 --> 00:14:30,038
of the Criminal Code
of the Soviet Union,

156
00:14:30,118 --> 00:14:33,918
resulting in a nuclear disaster
on April 26, 1986.

157
00:14:34,958 --> 00:14:37,318
The State calls witnesses
Comrade Khomyuk

158
00:14:37,398 --> 00:14:39,718
of the Byelorussian Nuclear Institute,

159
00:14:39,798 --> 00:14:43,638
Comrade Legasov of the Kurchatov
Institute of Atomic Energy,

160
00:14:44,398 --> 00:14:47,558
and Comrade Boris
Evdokimovich Shcherbina,

161
00:14:48,199 --> 00:14:50,598
Deputy Chairman of
the Council of Ministers

162
00:14:50,678 --> 00:14:53,358
and head of the Bureau
for Fuel and Energy.

163
00:15:26,758 --> 00:15:30,798
It began with,
of all things, a safety test.

164
00:15:31,958 --> 00:15:34,598
Why was there need
for a safety test at all?

165
00:15:35,278 --> 00:15:38,318
Reactor number 4 was not new
when the accident occurred.

166
00:15:39,038 --> 00:15:43,518
In fact, it went into operation
on December 20th, 1983.

167
00:15:44,398 --> 00:15:47,398
Eleven days later,
on the last day of the year,

168
00:15:48,278 --> 00:15:52,518
plant director Viktor Bryukhanov
signed this document,

169
00:15:53,878 --> 00:15:58,678
certifying the completion
of the construction of the reactor.

170
00:16:00,598 --> 00:16:03,518
As a result of finishing the work
before the end of the year,

171
00:16:04,878 --> 00:16:08,438
Comrade Bryukhanov was awarded
Hero of Socialist Labor.

172
00:16:09,358 --> 00:16:12,718
Comrade Fomin was awarded
for Valorous Labor.

173
00:16:13,118 --> 00:16:16,998
Comrade Dyatlov was given
an Order of the Red Banner.

174
00:16:19,318 --> 00:16:21,678
But their work was not finished.

175
00:16:23,318 --> 00:16:26,398
And this document was a lie.

176
00:16:27,958 --> 00:16:30,198
In order to sign this certificate,

177
00:16:30,438 --> 00:16:34,478
all safety tests had to have
been successfully completed,

178
00:16:34,558 --> 00:16:36,278
and yet, one remained.

179
00:16:39,598 --> 00:16:43,638
A nuclear reactor generates
heat in the core here.

180
00:16:44,558 --> 00:16:46,718
A series of pumps, here and here,

181
00:16:46,798 --> 00:16:49,718
send a constant flow of cooling water
through the core.

182
00:16:50,198 --> 00:16:52,598
The core's heat
turns the water to steam,

183
00:16:52,678 --> 00:16:54,878
and the steam spins the turbine here,

184
00:16:54,958 --> 00:16:56,518
and the result is electricity.

185
00:16:57,278 --> 00:16:59,998
But what if a power plant
has no power?

186
00:17:01,718 --> 00:17:04,438
What if the power feeding
the plant itself is disrupted?

187
00:17:05,198 --> 00:17:09,398
A blackout, equipment failure,
or an attack by a foreign enemy?

188
00:17:10,438 --> 00:17:12,238
If there's no power,

189
00:17:12,318 --> 00:17:14,958
the pumps cannot move
water through the core.

190
00:17:15,358 --> 00:17:17,678
And without water, the core overheats,

191
00:17:17,758 --> 00:17:19,238
the fuel melts down.

192
00:17:19,318 --> 00:17:21,718
In short, a nuclear disaster.

193
00:17:21,798 --> 00:17:22,878
The solution?

194
00:17:23,438 --> 00:17:26,638
Three diesel fuel
backup generators here.

195
00:17:27,198 --> 00:17:28,918
So, problem solved?

196
00:17:29,278 --> 00:17:30,598
No.

197
00:17:31,158 --> 00:17:33,598
Bryukhanov knew that the problem
was not solved at all.

198
00:17:34,118 --> 00:17:36,918
The backup generators took
approximately one minute

199
00:17:36,998 --> 00:17:39,278
to reach the speed required

200
00:17:39,358 --> 00:17:41,478
to power the pumps
and prevent a meltdown,

201
00:17:41,557 --> 00:17:44,437
and by that time,
it would be too late.

202
00:17:45,798 --> 00:17:47,598
So we arrive at the safety test.

203
00:17:49,718 --> 00:17:51,038
The theory was this,

204
00:17:51,118 --> 00:17:53,238
if the facility lost power,

205
00:17:53,318 --> 00:17:55,118
the turbine, which had been spinning,

206
00:17:55,198 --> 00:17:57,958
would take some time
to slow down and stop.

207
00:17:58,038 --> 00:18:01,678
What if you could take the electricity
it was still generating

208
00:18:01,758 --> 00:18:03,158
and transfer it to the pumps?

209
00:18:03,238 --> 00:18:06,918
What if the dying turbine could keep
the pumps working long enough

210
00:18:06,998 --> 00:18:10,918
to bridge the 60-second gap
until the generators came on?

211
00:18:15,878 --> 00:18:17,158
Any questions?

212
00:18:18,678 --> 00:18:21,758
No. Continue, please.

213
00:18:23,558 --> 00:18:25,758
To test this theory,

214
00:18:25,838 --> 00:18:30,078
the reactor is placed in a reduced
power mode, 700 megawatts,

215
00:18:30,158 --> 00:18:31,838
to simulate a blackout condition.

216
00:18:32,878 --> 00:18:34,718
Then the turbines are turned off,

217
00:18:34,958 --> 00:18:36,678
and as they slowly spin down,

218
00:18:36,758 --> 00:18:38,518
their electrical output is measured

219
00:18:38,598 --> 00:18:41,438
to see if it's enough
to power the pumps.

220
00:18:42,078 --> 00:18:43,518
The science is strong,

221
00:18:44,478 --> 00:18:49,037
but a test is only as good
as the men carrying it out.

222
00:18:50,398 --> 00:18:53,198
Now, the first time they tried,
they failed.

223
00:18:53,878 --> 00:18:56,078
The second time they tried,
they failed.

224
00:18:56,558 --> 00:18:58,758
The third time they tried,
they failed.

225
00:18:59,438 --> 00:19:02,038
The fourth time they tried

226
00:19:02,118 --> 00:19:05,598
was April 26th, 1986.

227
00:19:17,278 --> 00:19:18,918
Comrade Khomyuk.

228
00:19:42,038 --> 00:19:43,718
To understand
what happened that night,

229
00:19:43,798 --> 00:19:45,758
we have to go back 10 hours earlier,

230
00:19:45,838 --> 00:19:49,078
April 25th, the day the test
was meant to take place.

231
00:19:49,158 --> 00:19:52,478
By 2:00 in the afternoon,
the reactor has been lowered by half

232
00:19:52,558 --> 00:19:55,557
from its normal output level
of 3,200 megawatts

233
00:19:55,638 --> 00:19:57,798
to 1,600 megawatts and is stable

234
00:19:57,877 --> 00:20:00,678
and ready to be reduced to its
final output level for the test,

235
00:20:00,757 --> 00:20:02,238
700 megawatts.

236
00:20:02,878 --> 00:20:06,358
But before they can proceed,
there is a phone call.

237
00:20:07,718 --> 00:20:10,598
Power grid officials in Kiev
say that they cannot afford

238
00:20:10,678 --> 00:20:13,838
a further reduction in the electricity
until after midnight.

239
00:20:13,918 --> 00:20:16,158
They are asking for a 10-hour delay.

240
00:20:17,398 --> 00:20:19,158
This is the first critical moment,

241
00:20:19,238 --> 00:20:21,757
the first link
in the chain of disaster.

242
00:20:21,838 --> 00:20:25,078
Competent management would have
insisted on canceling the test.

243
00:20:26,238 --> 00:20:28,877
These three men allowed it to proceed.

244
00:20:30,718 --> 00:20:32,558
Why was this delay so dangerous?

245
00:20:32,878 --> 00:20:34,718
It created two problems.

246
00:20:35,358 --> 00:20:37,438
One of them is scientific in nature,

247
00:20:39,078 --> 00:20:40,677
and the other is very human.

248
00:20:41,878 --> 00:20:43,638
This is the one
we will consider first.

249
00:20:44,638 --> 00:20:48,438
<i>At midnight, there is a shift change.</i>

250
00:21:01,397 --> 00:21:02,357
Hey.

251
00:21:03,157 --> 00:21:05,637
-Khodemchuk...
-Forget it. Find another fool.

252
00:21:06,358 --> 00:21:08,558
Toptunov, want to buy a motorcycle?

253
